9
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:33,000
I asked about the Casimir effect last time.

10
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:38,000
Does everybody know what the Casimir effect is?

11
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Well, it's an effect of quantum field theory.

12
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:50,000
It can be described in a number of ways.

13
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:56,000
But it's just if you take two reflecting surfaces,

14
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:01,000
hold them a certain distance apart,

15
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:07,000
then there are effects of quantum field theory.

16
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Roughly speaking, you can say that

17
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:15,000
let's not have the conducting plates there.

18
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:20,000
Then there's a vacuum energy, and the vacuum energy

19
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:25,000
can be thought of as coming from virtual production

20
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:26,000
of pairs of particles.

21
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:28,000
It's one way to think about it.

22
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,500
You can also think of it

23
00:01:30,500 --> 00:01:33,000
as the zero-point energy of oscillators,

24
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:35,000
harmonic oscillators that are

25
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
associated with the quantum fields.

26
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:40,000
Same thing.

27
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:45,000
And in empty space, purely empty space,

28
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:49,500
there's a certain amount of energy that's

29
00:01:49,500 --> 00:01:54,000
present as a consequence of these virtual processes.

30
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:54,500
Now, the virtual processes also

31
00:01:54,500 --> 00:01:55,000
have a certain amount of energy.

32
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,500
And the virtual processes also take place

33
00:01:57,500 --> 00:02:00,000
in the presence of these conducting plates.

34
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:04,000
But the conducting plates kind of interrupt these processes.

35
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:08,000
For example, roughly speaking, virtual loops,

36
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:12,500
which would have been present

37
00:02:12,500 --> 00:02:17,000
in the vicinity of these plates,

38
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,000
had the plates not been present,

39
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,000
are going to get affected by these reflecting plates.

40
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:23,000
For example,

41
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,500
if there's a reflecting pair of

42
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:30,000
plates and the loop here of photons,

43
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:34,000
the photons, roughly speaking, will reflect off the plates.

44
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:40,000
So the virtual processes will be kind of interrupted

45
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
by the presence of these plates in

46
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
ways that would not have been there

47
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:48,000
if the plates had not been there.

48
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:49,000
That's all.

49
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:50,500
There is an effect of

50
00:02:50,500 --> 00:02:52,000
the plates on the virtual processes.

51
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,500
The virtual photons in the vacuum get

52
00:02:55,500 --> 00:02:59,000
reflected off the reflecting surfaces and so forth.

53
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:05,000
And that modifies the value of the energy density,

54
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:08,000
the vacuum energy density between the plates.

55
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:12,000
Also somewhat on the outsides of the plates.

56
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,000
If you take the plates far apart,

57
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:19,000
very, very far apart,

58
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:21,000
then it's true that each plate by itself

59
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:27,000
still does some interrupting of the vacuum diagrams

60
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:29,000
and modifies the energy.

61
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:31,500
But it modifies the energy in a way

62
00:03:31,500 --> 00:03:34,000
which depends on the distance between the plates.

63
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,000
Far away you get one answer.

64
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
As you bring them together,

65
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,000
more complicated things can happen.

66
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
Photons can bounce back,

67
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:45,000
virtual photons can bounce back and forth between them.

68
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:48,000
And the result is that the vacuum energy,

69
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:50,000
or the zero-point energy,

70
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:52,500
becomes a function of the

71
00:03:52,500 --> 00:03:55,000
distance between the reflecting plates.

72
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:58,000
When energy is a function of distance,

73
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:02,000
that is an indication that there's a force.

74
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
You can think of the energy

75
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:11,000
as a function of the distance between the plates,

76
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,000
and you can think of it as potential energy.

77
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,000
The derivative of that potential

78
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,000
energy with respect to distance

79
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:19,000
is a form of force.

80
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:23,000
So there's a quantum field-theoretic origin of force

81
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,000
between reflecting plates,

82
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:30,000
which disappears rather rapidly as you separate the plates.

83
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
I think it goes as one

84
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,000
over the distance to the sixth power,

85
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:35,000
if I remember?

86
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:36,000
Fourth power?

87
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:37,000
Fourth power.

88
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:39,000
So much faster than...

89
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:42,000
The force goes as a fourth power or the energy?

90
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
I can't remember.

91
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,500
Yeah, you can work it out

92
00:04:47,500 --> 00:04:50,000
just on dimensional grounds, in fact.

93
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:52,000
But I won't do that right now.

94
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:58,000
And that creates a force between the plates,

95
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
which is typically attractive.

96
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
So that's a detail that you have to work out.

97
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:05,000
The force is attractive.

98
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:07,000
In fact, if these were fermion loops here,

99
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:10,000
the force would probably have the opposite sign, I think.

100
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,000
So this is regard...

101
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:15,000
And this force can be measured.

102
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:16,000
It actually is measured.

103
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,000
It's difficult to measure.

104
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:18,000
It's a very small force,

105
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,000
and it falls off rapidly,

106
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,000
and it's difficult with separation.

107
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:27,000
But it's often taken to be a confirmation

108
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,000
of the idea of vacuum energy.

109
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:32,000
It is to some extent,

110
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
but on the other hand,

111
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,000
you can also just think of it

112
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:38,000
as a force between the plates

113
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,000
when they get close together.

114
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:43,000
Anyway, you asked me about the Casimir effect.

115
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:45,000
The question is,

116
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:48,000
what other confirmation is there of the vacuum energy?

117
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,000
Because that is such a small effect,

118
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
and it's not a big deal.

119
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
So what is the vacuum energy?

120
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Well, there's all kinds of processes

121
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:06,000
and detailed high-precision behaviors

122
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,000
of atoms and so forth,

123
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,000
atomic spectra and so forth,

124
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,000
which are sensitive to these vacuum loops.

125
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:17,000
Yeah, so they're indirect measurements.

