01:12:19,834 --> 01:12:21,834
So like any really, really small number,

1660
01:12:21,834 --> 01:12:24,834
its square can be taken to be zero.

1661
01:12:24,834 --> 01:12:28,834
So Grassman coordinates are small,

1662
01:12:28,834 --> 01:12:31,334
but nevertheless, they are important

1663
01:12:31,334 --> 01:12:33,834
to the structure of the theory.

1664
01:12:33,834 --> 01:12:36,834
And then the way a supersymmetric theory is set up

1665
01:12:36,834 --> 01:12:38,834
is by defining a Lagrange density,

1666
01:12:38,834 --> 01:12:40,834
and we'll talk about this a little bit.

1667
01:12:40,834 --> 01:12:41,834
I was going to go

1668
01:12:41,834 --> 01:12:42,834
into this a little bit tonight,

1669
01:12:42,834 --> 01:12:44,834
but it's getting a little too late.

1670
01:12:44,834 --> 01:12:48,834
But it's a Lagrange density which,

1671
01:12:48,834 --> 01:12:49,834
oh, first of all,

1672
01:12:49,834 --> 01:12:52,834
no, before we get to the Lagrange density,

1673
01:12:52,834 --> 01:12:55,834
let's talk about fields.

1674
01:12:55,834 --> 01:13:01,834
Fields ordinarily are functions of the x's.

1675
01:13:01,834 --> 01:13:04,834
Let's call them phi of x.

1676
01:13:04,834 --> 01:13:07,834
That's normally the way we think about fields.

1677
01:13:07,834 --> 01:13:09,834
But in a supersymmetric theory,

1678
01:13:09,834 --> 01:13:15,834
the fields are functions of x and the thetas.

1679
01:13:15,834 --> 01:13:16,834
So it's as if, indeed,

1680
01:13:16,834 --> 01:13:18,834
there were additional dimensions of space,

1681
01:13:18,834 --> 01:13:20,834
and fields can depend on

1682
01:13:20,834 --> 01:13:22,834
both the x's and the thetas.

1683
01:13:22,834 --> 01:13:27,834
Now, the theta dependence is very limited.

1684
01:13:27,834 --> 01:13:29,834
Why is it limited?

1685
01:13:29,834 --> 01:13:30,834
Imagine expanding.

1686
01:13:30,834 --> 01:13:34,834
Let's suppose that this phi was an ordinary number,

1687
01:13:34,834 --> 01:13:37,834
as opposed to a Grassman number.

1688
01:13:37,834 --> 01:13:41,834
Then you would write that this ordinary number,

1689
01:13:41,834 --> 01:13:45,834
phi of x and theta,

1690
01:13:45,834 --> 01:13:48,834
let's make this a capital phi,

1691
01:13:48,834 --> 01:13:50,834
it's called a superfield.

1692
01:13:50,834 --> 01:13:52,834
It's called a superfield because it,

1693
01:13:52,834 --> 01:13:53,834
not because,

1694
01:13:53,834 --> 01:13:55,834
but it's called a superfield,

1695
01:13:55,834 --> 01:13:58,834
and it depends on position,

1696
01:13:58,834 --> 01:14:00,834
ordinary position, space and time,

1697
01:14:00,834 --> 01:14:02,834
and these Grassman variables.

1698
01:14:02,834 --> 01:14:03,834
All right, now,

1699
01:14:03,834 --> 01:14:08,834
you can take any function of Grassman variables

1700
01:14:08,834 --> 01:14:13,834
and expand it in powers of the Grassman variables.

1701
01:14:13,834 --> 01:14:15,834
Let's suppose, for example,

1702
01:14:15,834 --> 01:14:18,834
there are four distinct thetas.

1703
01:14:18,834 --> 01:14:21,834
This is correct for an ordinary supersymmetric theory.

1704
01:14:21,834 --> 01:14:23,834
We'll understand why, but not right now.

1705
01:14:23,834 --> 01:14:24,834
There are four thetas,

1706
01:14:24,834 --> 01:14:27,834
theta one, theta two, theta three, and theta four.

1707
01:14:27,834 --> 01:14:30,834
They can be combined into two complex thetas,

1708
01:14:30,834 --> 01:14:32,834
but let's just take them as four thetas.

1709
01:14:32,834 --> 01:14:36,834
Then phi of x and theta can be expanded.

1710
01:14:36,834 --> 01:14:40,834
Phi, let's call it little phi now,

1711
01:14:40,834 --> 01:14:44,834
phi of x,

1712
01:14:44,834 --> 01:14:46,834
which is independent of theta,

1713
01:14:46,834 --> 01:14:48,834
it's a power series expansion in the theta,

1714
01:14:48,834 --> 01:14:55,834
plus, let's call it theta alpha,

1715
01:14:55,834 --> 01:14:58,834
psi alpha,

1716
01:14:58,834 --> 01:15:00,834
alpha is just some index

1717
01:15:00,834 --> 01:15:03,834
which labels the various Grassman numbers in the problem,

1718
01:15:03,834 --> 01:15:05,834
four of them in this case,

1719
01:15:05,834 --> 01:15:07,834
these,

1720
01:15:07,834 --> 01:15:09,834
then there might be something proportional

1721
01:15:09,834 --> 01:15:12,834
to theta alpha, theta beta,

1722
01:15:12,834 --> 01:15:14,834
times, I don't know,

1723
01:15:14,834 --> 01:15:16,834
give me a name of another field,

1724
01:15:16,834 --> 01:15:18,834
uh,

1725
01:15:18,834 --> 01:15:21,834
sine z,

1726
01:15:21,834 --> 01:15:24,834
z alpha beta,

1727
01:15:24,834 --> 01:15:26,834
this is also a function of x,

1728
01:15:26,834 --> 01:15:28,834
this is also a function of x,

1729
01:15:28,834 --> 01:15:31,334
and so it goes until you

1730
01:15:31,334 --> 01:15:33,834
get to four powers of theta.

1731
01:15:33,834 --> 01:15:36,834
All four thetas had better be different.

1732
01:15:36,834 --> 01:15:38,834
They also have to be different here

1733
01:15:38,834 --> 01:15:41,834
because any theta squared is zero.

1734
01:15:41,834 --> 01:15:43,834
So you can have theta one times theta two,

1735
01:15:43,834 --> 01:15:45,834
but you can't have theta one squared.

1736
01:15:45,834 --> 01:15:46,834
Not allowed.

1737
01:15:46,834 --> 01:15:47,834
And eventually you get to theta one,

1738
01:15:47,834 --> 01:15:48,834
theta two,

1739
01:15:48,834 --> 01:15:49,834
theta three,

1740
01:15:49,834 --> 01:15:50,834
theta four,

1741
01:15:50,834 --> 01:15:52,834
times some other thing,

1742
01:15:52,834 --> 01:15:53,834
I don't know,

1743
01:15:53,834 --> 01:15:54,834
we need to give it a name,

1744
01:15:54,834 --> 01:15:57,834
d of x.

1745
01:15:57,834 --> 01:15:59,834
And then there is no more than that.

1746
01:15:59,834 --> 01:16:01,834
There is no more than that.

1747
01:16:01,834 --> 01:16:03,834
Another way of saying it

1748
01:16:03,834 --> 01:16:05,834
is that the super field

1749
01:16:05,834 --> 01:16:09,834
is composed of several ordinary fields.

1750
01:16:09,834 --> 01:16:12,834
A boson field, phi of x,

1751
01:16:12,834 --> 01:16:15,834
a fermion field, psi,

1752
01:16:15,834 --> 01:16:17,834
why do I say it's a fermion field?

1753
01:16:17,834 --> 01:16:20,834
Well, because it has to be a Grassmann number.

1754
01:16:20,834 --> 01:16:22,834
Grassmann number times Grassmann number

1755
01:16:22,834 --> 01:16:23,834
is an ordinary number.

1756
01:16:23,834 --> 01:16:26,834
And then another boson type field.

1757
01:16:26,834 --> 01:16:28,834
And then, and so it goes,

1758
01:16:28,834 --> 01:16:31,834
a finite number of them,

1759
01:16:31,834 --> 01:16:33,834
a finite multiplet,

1760
01:16:33,834 --> 01:16:35,834
a finite multiplet of fields

1761
01:16:35,834 --> 01:16:41,834
associated with different particles.

1762
01:16:41,834 --> 01:16:43,834
And so you can either think of it

1763
01:16:43,834 --> 01:16:45,834
as a collection of ordinary fields,

1764
01:16:45,834 --> 01:16:47,834
or you can group them together

1765
01:16:47,834 --> 01:16:49,834
and do the bookkeeping by saying

1766
01:16:49,834 --> 01:16:51,834
there's an additional family of

1767
01:16:51,834 --> 01:16:53,834
Grassmann coordinates,

1768
01:16:53,834 --> 01:16:55,834
and the field can be expanded

1769
01:16:55,834 --> 01:16:57,834
in those Grassmann coordinates.

1770
01:16:57,834 --> 01:16:59,834
So it's a kind of bookkeeping.

1771
01:16:59,834 --> 01:17:02,834
Once you have the idea of a super field,

1772
01:17:02,834 --> 01:17:05,834
you can then write a Lagrangian,

1773
01:17:05,834 --> 01:17:08,834
a Lagrange density,

1774
01:17:08,834 --> 01:17:13,834
which depends on the x's and the theta's,

1775
01:17:13,834 --> 01:17:15,834
and it's built up,

1776
01:17:15,834 --> 01:17:18,834
out of these super fields,

1777
01:17:18,834 --> 01:17:19,834
products of them,

1778
01:17:19,834 --> 01:17:21,834
functions of them,

1779
01:17:21,834 --> 01:17:25,834
various kinds of derivatives of them.

1780
01:17:25,834 --> 01:17:27,834
I won't bother writing down

1781
01:17:27,834 --> 01:17:29,834
a specific Lagrangian,

1782
01:17:29,834 --> 01:17:32,834
but it's built out of the super fields.

1783
01:17:32,834 --> 01:17:34,834
And that Lagrangian,

1784
01:17:34,834 --> 01:17:35,834
the Lagrangian density,

1785
01:17:35,834 --> 01:17:39,834
depends on x and theta.

1786
01:17:39,834 --> 01:17:42,834
And the important question is always,

1787
01:17:42,834 --> 01:17:43,834
when you have a Lagrangian,

1788
01:17:43,834 --> 01:17:45,834
what do you do with a Lagrangian?

1789
01:17:45,834 --> 01:17:48,834
You integrate it to find an action.

1790
01:17:48,834 --> 01:17:50,834
And then in classical physics,

1791
01:17:50,834 --> 01:17:53,834
it's either the principle of least action,

1792
01:17:53,834 --> 01:17:55,834
or you use the Lagrangian

1793
01:17:55,834 --> 01:17:57,834
in Feynman's path integral formulation

1794
01:17:57,834 --> 01:17:59,834
of quantum mechanics.

1795
01:17:59,834 --> 01:18:02,834
The important thing is the action.

1796
01:18:02,834 --> 01:18:04,834
The action ordinarily

1797
01:18:04,834 --> 01:18:07,834
is an integral of the Lagrange density

1798
01:18:07,834 --> 01:18:11,834
over the four dimensions of space,

1799
01:18:11,834 --> 01:18:13,834
but now it also becomes

1800
01:18:13,834 --> 01:18:15,834
an integration of the Lagrange density.

1801
01:18:15,834 --> 01:18:19,834
And then over the various thetas.

1802
01:18:22,834 --> 01:18:26,834
That is the structure of supersymmetric theories

1803
01:18:26,834 --> 01:18:28,834
that everything is exactly as if

1804
01:18:28,834 --> 01:18:32,834
there were some additional directions of space,

1805
01:18:32,834 --> 01:18:36,834
and the action of the theory

1806
01:18:36,834 --> 01:18:39,834
becomes an integral not only over ordinary space,

1807
01:18:39,834 --> 01:18:42,834
but also over the thetas.

1808
01:18:42,834 --> 01:18:44,834
Now that raises a question.

1809
01:18:44,834 --> 01:18:47,834
What the devil do we mean by the integral

1810
01:18:47,834 --> 01:18:50,834
over Grassman variables?

1811
01:18:50,834 --> 01:18:53,834
What do we mean by taking a function

1812
01:18:53,834 --> 01:18:55,834
of Grassman variables

1813
01:18:55,834 --> 01:18:57,834
and integrating it over theta?

1814
01:18:57,834 --> 01:19:02,834
That's obviously an as yet undefined concept.

1815
01:19:02,834 --> 01:19:05,834
I think we did define the arithmetic

1816
01:19:05,834 --> 01:19:08,833
of Grassman variables.

1817
01:19:08,833 --> 01:19:11,833
You can add them, you can multiply them,

1818
01:19:11,833 --> 01:19:13,833
you can do usual arithmetic operations.

1819
01:19:14,834 --> 01:19:16,834
Don't try dividing by them.

1820
01:19:16,834 --> 01:19:18,834
That gets a little dicey.

1821
01:19:18,834 --> 01:19:21,834
But adding and multiplying is an okay thing to do.

1822
01:19:21,834 --> 01:19:25,834
You can do the differential calculus.

1823
01:19:25,834 --> 01:19:28,834
The differential calculus is very simple.

1824
01:19:28,834 --> 01:19:31,834
If you want to differentiate with respect to a theta,

1825
01:19:31,834 --> 01:19:34,834
you do more or less the obvious thing.

1826
01:19:34,834 --> 01:19:36,834
If you want to differentiate with respect to theta one,

1827
01:19:36,834 --> 01:19:39,834
you just find out where theta one appears in here.

1828
01:19:39,834 --> 01:19:40,834
Here it is.

1829
01:19:40,834 --> 01:19:41,834
It could appear here.

1830
01:19:41,834 --> 01:19:43,834
And you're just differentiating with respect to theta one.

1831
01:19:43,834 --> 01:19:45,834
You're just differentiating with respect to it.

1832
01:19:45,834 --> 01:19:48,834
It just differentiates exactly the way

1833
01:19:48,834 --> 01:19:51,834
you would ordinarily differentiate.

1834
01:19:51,834 --> 01:19:55,834
You don't have to worry about higher powers of theta.

1835
01:19:55,834 --> 01:19:58,834
A given theta can only appear to a linear order

1836
01:19:58,834 --> 01:19:59,834
and no higher.

1837
01:19:59,834 --> 01:20:03,834
So the table of derivatives is very, very simple.

1838
01:20:03,834 --> 01:20:06,834
The derivative of a constant is zero.

1839
01:20:06,834 --> 01:20:09,834
The derivative of something proportional to theta

1840
01:20:09,834 --> 01:20:11,834
is just a proportionality factor.

1841
01:20:11,834 --> 01:20:12,834
And that's it.

1842
01:20:12,834 --> 01:20:14,834
It's a simple table of derivatives.

1843
01:20:14,834 --> 01:20:19,334
The question is what do we

1844
01:20:19,334 --> 01:20:23,834
mean by the integral over thetas

1845
01:20:23,834 --> 01:20:26,834
of Grassmann variables.

1846
01:20:26,834 --> 01:20:33,834
And I'm going to tell you now the justification

1847
01:20:33,834 --> 01:20:37,834
for the rules of integration is that they're useful.

1848
01:20:37,834 --> 01:20:40,834
That they're useful in various contexts.

1849
01:20:40,834 --> 01:20:42,834
It's completely abstract.

1850
01:20:42,834 --> 01:20:46,834
An integral is not in any sense a sum.

1851
01:20:46,834 --> 01:20:49,834
The integrals over Grassmann variables are analogous

1852
01:20:49,834 --> 01:20:51,834
to definite integrals.

1853
01:20:51,834 --> 01:20:53,834
They're not indefinite integrals.

1854
01:20:53,834 --> 01:20:55,834
They're thought of as definite integrals.

1855
01:20:55,834 --> 01:20:58,834
So when you integrate over theta here,

1856
01:20:58,834 --> 01:21:00,834
you're doing a definite integral

1857
01:21:00,834 --> 01:21:02,834
over the entire theta space.

1858
01:21:02,834 --> 01:21:06,834
I won't bother writing from minus infinity to infinity

1859
01:21:06,834 --> 01:21:08,834
because theta is a tiny

1860
01:21:08,834 --> 01:21:10,834
variable which doesn't vary very much.

1861
01:21:10,834 --> 01:21:12,834
But here's a little bit of a reference.

1862
01:21:12,834 --> 01:21:15,334
It's the, there's no sense,

1863
01:21:15,334 --> 01:21:17,834
no analog of an indefinite integral.

1864
01:21:17,834 --> 01:21:19,834
There's only the analog, yeah.

1865
01:21:19,834 --> 01:21:21,834
By saying there's no indefinite integral,

1866
01:21:21,834 --> 01:21:23,834
are you getting away from saying that the integral

1867
01:21:23,834 --> 01:21:25,834
is the opposite of the derivative?

1868
01:21:25,834 --> 01:21:28,834
Very much you are getting away from that

1869
01:21:28,834 --> 01:21:30,834
because as it turns out, the integral and the derivative

1870
01:21:30,834 --> 01:21:32,834
are exactly the same thing.

1871
01:21:32,834 --> 01:21:34,834
Right.

1872
01:21:34,834 --> 01:21:39,834
With the d4x, we're reading over all of space-time.

1873
01:21:39,834 --> 01:21:40,834
Yeah.

1874
01:21:40,834 --> 01:21:41,834
So that's also a definite integral.

1875
01:21:41,834 --> 01:21:43,834
It is also a definite integral, yes.

1876
01:21:43,834 --> 01:21:45,834
Yes.

1877
01:21:45,834 --> 01:21:46,834
Yes.

1878
01:21:46,834 --> 01:21:48,834
So I'm just going to tell you,

1879
01:21:48,834 --> 01:21:52,834
for the purposes of knowing exactly what's written here,

1880
01:21:52,834 --> 01:21:55,834
I'm going to tell you

1881
01:21:55,834 --> 01:21:58,834
what the table of integrals is

1882
01:21:58,834 --> 01:22:02,834
for a, for Grassman integration.

1883
01:22:02,834 --> 01:22:10,834
And then we can start to talk a little bit

1884
01:22:10,834 --> 01:22:14,834
about supersymmetric theories and how you construct them.

1885
01:22:14,834 --> 01:22:15,834
How you construct them,

1886
01:22:15,834 --> 01:22:18,834
but the main point of supersymmetric theories

1887
01:22:18,834 --> 01:22:21,834
is that they, whatever they do,

1888
01:22:21,834 --> 01:22:26,834
they preserve the symmetry between bosons and fermions.

1889
01:22:26,834 --> 01:22:30,834
They ensure the delicate cancellations.

1890
01:22:30,834 --> 01:22:32,834
If you construct them properly,

1891
01:22:32,834 --> 01:22:36,834
they can be complicated, interacting field theories,

1892
01:22:36,834 --> 01:22:39,834
but they will always preserve in the same way

1893
01:22:39,834 --> 01:22:45,834
that if you construct ordinary field theories carefully,

1894
01:22:45,834 --> 01:22:48,834
they will preserve Lorentz invariance.

1895
01:22:48,834 --> 01:22:50,834
They will preserve rotation invariance.

1896
01:22:50,834 --> 01:22:53,834
They will preserve the various invariances

1897
01:22:53,834 --> 01:22:55,834
that you built into the Lagrangian.

1898
01:22:55,834 --> 01:22:57,834
In the same way,

1899
01:22:57,834 --> 01:23:00,334
by being careful to at

1900
01:23:00,334 --> 01:23:02,834
every step preserve the supersymmetry,

1901
01:23:02,834 --> 01:23:06,834
you can ensure that at the end of the day

1902
01:23:06,834 --> 01:23:08,834
that these delicate cancellations,

1903
01:23:08,834 --> 01:23:11,834
or Feynman diagrams and things like that,

1904
01:23:11,834 --> 01:23:17,834
are preserved and don't get ruined by interactions,

1905
01:23:17,834 --> 01:23:21,834
by all the various complexities in the theory.

1906
01:23:21,834 --> 01:23:23,834
That's the point of it.

1907
01:23:23,834 --> 01:23:25,834
So the point of it is

1908
01:23:25,834 --> 01:23:27,834
to set up a kind of calculus

1909
01:23:27,834 --> 01:23:30,834
of how to construct supersymmetric theories.

1910
01:23:30,834 --> 01:23:31,834
That's what we're doing.

1911
01:23:31,834 --> 01:23:33,834
We're attempting to build a calculus

